SIMPLE: fecundate
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fecundate
<hw>Fec"un*date</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Fecundated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Fecundating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>fecundare</ets>, fr. <ets>fecundus</ets>. See
<er>Fecund</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To make fruitful or
prolific.</def> <rj><au>W. Montagu.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Biol.)</fld> <def>To render fruitful or prolific;
to impregnate; <as>as, in flowers the pollen <ex>fecundates</ex> the
ovum through the stigma</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fecundation</ent>⟦br⟧
